Introduction: There are profound changes that take place in drug metabolism
enzymes during fetal and postnatal development. These changes may
significantly impact drug therapy in children.
Areas covered: A combination of focused and comprehensive literature
searches using PubMed and reference lists (from inception to 7 November
2009) is undertaken to identify reports on in vitro and in vivo development
of drug metabolism enzymes as well disposition of selected drugs and their
effect in children. The article provides an update on development of drug
metabolism enzymes and their impact on drug substrate disposition and dis-
ease, which may aid to improve clinical practice and optimally design clinical
trials in children.
Expert opinion: Drug metabolism enzyme activity changes profoundly
throughout the continuum of postnatal development and often results in
different disposition pathways than in adults. Genetics and co-morbidity
interact significantly with these developmental changes. Translation of exist-
ing knowledge into age-adjusted dosing guidelines and clinical trial design is
highly needed for there to be an improvement in drug therapy in children.
Keywords: child, drug metabolism, fetus, ontogeny, pharmacodynamics, pharmacogenetics,
pharmacokinetics
Expert Opin. Drug Metab. Toxicol. (2011) 7(8):935-948
1. Introduction
Drug metabolizing enzymes play an important role in the disposition of drugs, toxic
agents and endogenous substrates. Developmental changes in these enzymes may,
therefore, largely impact pharmacokinetics and consequent pharmacodynamics in
children. Ontogeny of drug metabolizing enzymes has been extensively studied in
animal and human tissue. In addition, the interplay of covariant genetics, disease
state and co-medicatio n with the ontogeny of drug metabolism ultimately
determines the fate of drugs in children. The aim of this review is to discuss the
impact of profound changes in drug metabolizing enzymes on drug substrate
disposition and effect in children. The direct effect of age and other covariants
on processes other than drug metabolism that govern pharma cokinetics
[1,2] or
pharmacodynamics
[3] in children is outside the scope of this review.
2. Effect of age on drug metabolizing enzymes
The clinical impact of ontogeny of drug metabolism became apparent, not primar-
ily by systematic research, but by clinical observation. In the late 1950s, newborn
infants developed the often lethal grey baby syndrome. These critically ill infants

all received chloramphenicol for neonatal sepsis, which accu-
mulated in the body due to immature glucuronidation by
UDP-glucuronosyltransferase (UGT)2B 7 with the observed
toxicity as a consequence
[4-6].
This and other observations spurred the research on the
ontogeny of drug metabolizing enzymes. From in vitro
research in the early 1970s emerged the global impression
that for many enzymes expression and content are low in
the fetus, with an increase of activity after birth. The exact
developmental pattern of individual enzyme activity remained
unclear. This in vitro research on the ontogeny of drug metab-
olizing enzymes has been hampered by the lack of tissue mate-
rial from children of different age groups. A large stride
forward in closing the information gap on ontogeny of drug
metabolizing enzymes in vitro was made by Hines who was
able to collect > 200 liver samples covering the whole fetal
and pediatric age range. An extensive, excellent review using
data from these studies in relation to previous studies showed
that the in vitro ontogeny of hepatic drug metabolizing
enzymes appears to follow three general patterns of expression
(
Figure 1) [7]. The first pattern is characterized by relatively
high expression during fetal life with expression maintained
at low or absent levels during postnatal life (e.g., CYP3A7,
FMO1 and SULT1A3). In the second pattern, some genes,
such as CYP3A5, SULT1A1 and TPMT, seem to be
expressed at relatively constant levels in the fetus and postnatal
life. The third pattern is characterized by enzymes that are
either not expressed in the fetus or only show activity late in
pregnancy or within hours to days after birth. This last group
includes CYP1A 2, 2C9, 2C19, 2D6, 2E1, 3A4, FMO3 and
most UGTs, and levels comparable to adults may not occur
until later in childhood.
Most of our knowledge on the develo pment of drug metab-
olizing enzymes in vivo is derived from pharmacokinetic (PK)
studies in neonates and older children. Plasma clearance of
drugs, administered as part of clinical care, may reflect the
in vivo ontogeny of individual or combined enzymes. Alterna-
tively, urinary metabolite:drug ratios or stable isotope labeled
probes have been used to study ontogeny of drug metabo-
lism
[8]. Ho wever, in vivo research, using probe drugs specific
to study individual enzyme activity, is limited in children due
to ethical and practical limitations.
3. Changes in individual drug metabolizing
enzymes
3.1 Cytochrome P450 enzymes
The cytochrome P450 superfamily consists of at least
29 enzymes, of which a large number is involved in drug
metabolism, while many CYPs also metabolize several toxi-
cants and endogenous substrates
[9,10]. Many CYPs are
polymorphically expressed, which may result in clinically
relevant inter-individual differences in drug metabolism for
some CYPs (e.g., CYP2D6, CYP2B6, CYP2C9, CYP2C19),
but not for others as recently reviewed by Johansson and
Ingelman-Sundber g
[11].
3.1.1 CYP1A2
The polymorphically expr essed CYP1A2 is involved in the
metabolism of > 20 drugs, for example, caffeine, theophylline,
olanzapine and zolmitriptan and melatonin
[11-16].
3.1.1.1 In vitro
CYP1A2 protein levels and in vitro activity are very low to
undetectable in fetal liver, with a slow developmental pattern
after birth
[17]. In the direct neonatal period 5%, at 1 year
25% and up to 6 years of age 50% of adult in vitro activity
was detected
[18].
3.1.1.2 In vivo
The in vitro developmental pattern mirrors in vivo ontogeny
when using caffeine as metabolic probe in children up to
18 months
[19]. In another study, newborns recruited from
well-baby nurseries at two local hospitals were phenotyped
also using caffeine six times between 2 weeks and 6 months
of postnatal age
[20]. Consistent with the previous results, an
increase in caffeine elimination was observed over this age
range. By 2 months of age, the average caffeine half-life was
already faster than that observed in 2-week-old infants. No
relationship with postmenstrual age was found. An unex-
pected finding of this study was that in neonates who are for-
mula-fed, CYP1A2 and also CYP3A4 activity rises more
rapidly than in neonates who are breastfed, although the
underlying reasons for this finding are unknown to date
[20].
Especially early after birth, caffeine clearance is low and
occurs mainly through renal filtration as unchanged
drug
[21]. Clearance strongly correlates with glomerular
Article highlights.
.
Drug metabolism enzymes (DMEs) show profound
changes during pre- and postnatal development, but
important information gaps remain on the exact
developmental pattern of most DMEs in the first 2 years
of life.
.
In children, specificity of drugs for individual enzymes
may differ from adults, further contributing to variations
in drug disposition, efficacy and safety in
this population.
.
Genetic variation in DMEs interacts with developmental
variation in DME activity, often obscuring or
emphasizing a genotype-phenotype relation.
.
Co-morbidity also significantly impacts activity of DMEs
in children.
.
The impact of developmental changes in drug
metabolism on drug efficacy and safety has been
studied increasingly; translation of existing knowledge to
dosing guidelines and clinical trial design is
highly needed.

3.1.2 CY2B6
CYP2B6 activity in vitro and in vivo shows large inter-
individual variation. Part of this variation is due to genetic
polymorphisms, the most studied is CYP2B6-516G>T or
CYP2B6*6. The CYP2B6*6/*6 genotype is more common
in African-Americans (20%) than in European-Americans
[26]
In addition, enzyme activity is highly inducible. Examples
of CYP2B6 substrates are bupropion
[27], ifosfamide [28],
efavirenz
[28], methadone [29] and the inactive prodrug
cyclophosphamide
[30].
3.1.2.1 In vitro
Only recently, the ontogeny of CYP2B6 was studied system-
atically in vitro
[31]. CYP2B6 protein content appears low
in early fetal life, even undetectable in about a third of
fetal liv er samples. In the first month of postnatal life,
CYP2B6 expression increases significantly but modestly
(only twofold increase) with large inter-individual variation.
Samples from African-Americans had lower CYP2B6 activity
than Caucasians, but this observation may be explained by a
younger age of the African-American donors
[31].
3.1.2.2 In vivo
The CYP2B6 substrate methadone is frequently used to treat
abstinence syndromes in neonates after a prolonged ICU stay
with associated prolonged opioid administration. Neonatal
cases of prolonged QTc syndrome in neonates prenatally
exposed by mothers using methadone
[32] can probably be
explained by developmentally low CYP2B6 activity in vivo
(in addition to CYP3A4, which is also involved in methadone
metabolism). Neonatal methadone dosing should take these

polymorphism
[35].
3.1.3 CYP2C
The CYP2C subfamily exists of CYP2C8, CYP2C9, CYP2C18
and CYP2C19 isoforms
[37]. All CYP2C isoforms show genetic
polymorphisms of which CYP2C9 and CYP2C19 and pro-
duce large inter-individual differences in drug response and
disposition. These isoenzymes metabolize many drugs
commonly used in children. CYP2C9 metabolizes for exam-
ple warfarin, phenytoin and NSAIDs (ibuprofen, indo-
methacin, diclofenac)
[38-43], but also nelfinavir, diazepam,
S-mephenytoin and clopidogrel
[43-47].
3.1.3.1 In vitro
The in vitro ontogeny can be characterized by CYP2C19 pro-
tein appearing relatively more abundant in pregnancy with a
change to more CYP2C9 protein in postnatal life
[48]. Average
CYP2C9 levels and activity were found at 50% of those in
adults throughout childhood. This may be explained by the
relative lack of samples from older children. Postnatal
CYP2C9 and CYP2C19 content and activity seem to develop
independent of ethnicity.
In vitro metabolism of arachidon ic acid (AA), an endoge-
nous substrate of CYP2C involved in the physiologic regula-
tion of vascular tone, was studied by Treluyer et al. They
showed that overall AA metabolism was extremely low during
the fetal period and rose after birth. Interestingly, in infants
with sudden infant death syndrome, individual CYP2C activ-
ity, as determined by in vitro AA metabolism, was higher than
in age-matched controls, suggesting that increased AA metab-
olism leads to dangerous pathophysiological changes in this
age group
[49,50]. The underlying reason for higher CYP2C
activity in these children is unknown.
3.1.3.2 In vivo
3.1.3.2.1 CYP2C9
Ibuprofen pharmacokinetics (a CYP2C9, and to a lesser
extent CYP2C8 substrate) seem to reflect in vitro develop-
mental data. The average adult racemic ibuprofen half-
life is 2 h, while in contrast S-ibuprofen half-life is very
long in preterm neonates up to 1 week of age (34 h with
no effect of postnatal age). For R-ibupr ofen, a combined
CYP2C9-- CYP2C8 substrate, elimination half-life sharply
decreases from an average of 8 h at day 1 to 0.5 h at day
8 postnatally
[51].
As CYP2C9 is im portant in S-ibuprofen metabolic clear-
ance, it was hypothesized that genetic variation in CYP2C9
might impact the succes s of ibuprofen therapy for closure of
patent ductus arteriosus in preterm infants
[52,53]. However,
such a relationship could not be found. This failure to dem-
onstrate a pharmacodynamic effect of CYP2C9 genotype
may possibly be explained by the interplay with ontogeny.
Developmentally low CYP2C9 activity, as supported by
reduced ibuprofen clearance, may obscure a genotype effect
on ibuprofen disposition and consequent efficacy to close
the PDA.
Clearance of warfarin, also a CYP2C9 substrate, normal-
ized for weight was higher in pre-pubertal children than
adults; however, after normalization for liver size, this differ-
ence disappeared
[54]. Importantly, young er children showed
higher international normalized ratio (INR):dose ratios,
which precludes automatic dose adjustment based on mere
pharmacokinetics alone. In contrast to the neonatal pharma-
cogenetic study of CYP2C9 and ibuprofen, in a warfarin
study of 29 older children with cancer, carriers of heterozy-
gous polymorphisms of CYP2C9 achieved target INR
sooner and more frequently had INR above the target level,
compared to children with the CYP2C9 wild type
[55].
Developmental changes in CYP2C9 activity may also explain
why infants are more susceptible to hepatotoxicity associated
with valproic acid therapy than older children and adults
[56].
This hepatotoxocity of valproic acid has been partially attrib-
uted to its metabolites, for example, 4-ene-VPA, which is
formed through CYP2C9- and CYP2A6-mediated metabolism.
The increased formation of this metabolite in younger children
suggests increased CYP2C9/2A6 activity in this age group.
However, these in vivo data are in contrast with the in vitro
data which show 50% of CYP2C9 levels and activity through-
out childhood when compared to adults
[48].Thisdiscrepancy
is possibly explained by the relative cytochrome abundance
due to a relatively larger liver size in children.
3.1.3.2.2 CYP2C19
The best studied CYP2C19 substrate in children is the proton
pump inhibitor pantoprazole. The mean estimates for half-
life of pantoprazole in newborns are much longer (2 -- 4h)
than for older children and adults (1 -- 1.5 h) with a sig-
nificant increase in the first 3 weeks of age, independent of
gestational age. For older children, the weight normalized

3.1.4 CYP2D6
CYP2D6 is polymorphically expressed; numerous SNPs have
been identified known to result in altered CYP2D6 activity.
An interesting discussion paper on the role of genotyping in
the context of ontogeny, using CYP2D6 as an example, was
recently published
[63]. Important pediatric CYP2D6 sub-
strates are opioids (e.g., codeine, tramadol), haloperidol,
diphenhydramine and b-blockers (timolol, propranolol,
metoprolol)
[64,65] [66-68].
3.1.4.1 In vitro
The ontogeny of CYP2D6 in vitro follows the pattern of low
or absent activity in the first trimester, with a parallel increase
in activity and protein content which remains stable, but low
(5% of adult activity) throughout the last trimester and the
first week of life, to stabilize thereafter. Conflicting data exist
on the developmental pattern after the first week of life. Ear-
lier studies showed a slow incline in CYP2D6 protein levels
activity after the first week of life
[69], and more recent data
showed an increase in CYP2D6 activity and content up to
2 weeks of age, with no change thereafter
[70]. These levels
are, however, in the low range of data from adults, but may
be due to an overrepresentation of samples from younger chil-
dren (< 1 year of age). Pediatri c samples from Cau casians
(n = 80) showed higher CYP2D6 activity than samples from
African-Americans (n = 57).
3.1.4.2 In vivo
Similar to these in vitro results, controversy exists on the
developmental pattern in vivo. Using dextromethorphan
urinary metabolite ratio as in vivo surrogate CYP2D6
measure, no further incre ase i n CYP2D6 activity after
2 weeks of postnatal life was found
[71].Theresultsofthis
study were disputed, as the maturation of renal excretion of
dextromethorphan and metabolites may have obs cured a
developmental pattern of CYP2D6 activity in the first year
of life
[72].
Using tramadol, the ontogeny of C YP2D6 was fur-
ther studied in pre term and ter m infants. Tramadol (M)
is metabolized by CYP2D6 to the active metabolite
O-demethyl tramadol (M1). Using population pharma-
cokinetics (1275 tramadol time-- concentration profiles in
57 neonates, 33 children and 32 adults), 50% of adult
clearance was reached at 44 weeks postmenstrual age, with
a maturational half-life in tramadol clearance of 3.6 weeks,
resulting in about 90% of adult t ramadol clearance capacity
at postnatal age of 1 year
[73]. In conclusion, especially after
the first weeks of life, the development of CYP2D6 is not
fully elucidated. It would be interesting to see if the analge-
sic efficacy of tramadol is reduced in preterm and y oung
neonates as the conversion of tramadol to its more active
metabolite is reduced. I t should b e taken in to accoun t,
however, that the plasma cle arance of the metabolite is
also impaired due t o developmental changes in renal func-
tion. Henc e, the overall metabolite concentration may be
higher than expected solely from C YP2D6 ontogeny, at a
limited time interval around 40 weeks of postmenstrual
age, as was elegantly shown by Allegaert et al.
[73].This
combined matur ation precludes an ea sy extrapolation of
adult data on the e ffect of CYP2D6 genotype to tramadol
analgesia and adverse events.
For, diphenhydramine, which is mainly metabolized by
CYP2D6, clearance rates were significantly higher in children
(mean age 8.9 ± 1.7 years) than in adults (49.2 ± 22.8 vs
23.3 ± 9.4 ml/min/kg)
[64]. These data may explain the lack
of an effect of diphenhydramine (1 mg/kg) on sleep in a ran-
domized controlled trial in 44 children aged 6 -- 15 years of
age. When combining the used dose with the PK data, the
expected drug exposure is lower than reported in adults to
result in adequate sleep
[74,75].
Similarly, the CYP2D6 substrate carvedilol shows faster
clearance in yo ung infants (2.7 l/h/kg) than in older children
(0.7 l/h/kg)
[76]. The effect of faster clearance and possibly
lower drug levels on the effect of this drug in young children
has not been studied to our knowledge.
As CYP2D6 is polymorphically expressed and CYP2D6
activity may mature rapidly from birth onwards, an effe ct of
CYP2D6 genotype could be anticipated already in the neona-
tal period. Indeed, in postnatal, but not fetal liver samples,
CYP2D6 activity and protein content were associated with
CYP2D6 genotype, independent of age
[70]. These findings
were corroborated in the population PK study on tramadol,
where tramadol clearance was also associated with CYP2D6
genotype after 40 weeks of postmenstrual age
[73]. The
combined effect of different matur ational processes may be

3.1.5 CYP3A
The most abundant cytochrome subfamily in human liver
is CYP3A, consisting of CYP3A4, CYP3A5, CYP3A7 and
CYP3A43
[10] [83]. Although genetic polymorphisms have
been found for CYP3A4 and CYP3A7, only the CYP3A5*3
polymorphism has show n evident clinical significance
[84].
It is estimated that > 50% of all metabolized drugs are
metabolized by CYP3A isoforms.
3.1.5.1 In vitro
In vitro studies have shown that CYP3A4 expression, content
and activity are low before birth, with a surge thereafter.
The exact developmental pattern after birth is still not fully
elucidated. In contrast, in vitro CYP3A7 activity is high during
gestation and accounts for 30 -- 50% of all fetal CYP
content
[85-87], with a rapid decline after birth. In a minority
of patients, CYP3A7 expression is continuous throughout
childhood and adulthood, partially related to a genetic variant,
CYP3A7*1C
[88]. CYP3A5 transcripts and protein were shown
in the first trimester, but in a limited number of the liver
samples studied
[89,90]. Polymorphic expression of CYP3A5,
with the CYP3A5*3 genotype resulting in absent protein,
may contribute to a lack of CYP3A5 in these samples
[89].
CYP3A5 protein was present from fetal life to adulthood and
protein content was relatively low in comparison to CYP3A7
and CYP3A4 levels
[89]. While substrate specificity for
CYP3A4 and CYP3A5 largely overlap, CYP3A7 shows quite
different substrate specificity. This has important implications
for drug disposition during the transition from fetal to adult
life and for studies looking at this transition.
3.1.5.2 In vivo
In adults, in vivo drug metabolism activity is determined
using specific surrogate probes. For CYP3A4/5 activity, mid-
azolam is the most validated and frequently used probe
drug
[91]. Moreover, midazolam plasm a clearance is strongly
correlated with in vitro CYP3A activity, when given as a small
single dose (0.075 mg/kg). Other probes used in children to
phenotype CYP3A4/5 are caffeine and dextromethorphan
urinary ratios as well as stable isotope labeled probes
[20,71,92].
Midazolam is a very weak substrate for CYP3A7 and
hence appears a good probe to study CYP3A4/5 ontogeny.
Midazolam clearance is very low in preterm and term neo-
nates in the first days after birth. No clear effect of gestational
age between 26 and 36 weeks can be found on midazolam
clearance
[93,94]. In the first year of life, midazolam clearance
increases dram atically. When corrected for bodyweight,
bodyweight normalized midazolam clearance (in milliliter/
kilogram/hour) appears higher in infancy than in older chil-
dren and adults
[95,96]. In contrast, a pooled midazolam PK
analysis, using average published PK estimates, could not
identify higher midazolam clearance rates in infants
[97].
In the neonate, differences in midazolam clearance due to
developmental changes in CYP3A4/5 on the neonate seem to
impact midazolam requirements during continuous infusion.
In critically preterm infants, the average midazolam infusion
rate for adequate sedation is 0.06 µg/kg/h
[98]; in older, criti-
cally ill children, median infusion requirements vary between
0.05 and 0.5 mg/kg/h
[99] [100]. Additionally, younger infants
(1 -- 3 years of age) more often display inadequate sedation
with midazolam up to 0.3 mg/kg/h than older children
[101].
This finding is suggestive of faster clearance in this age
group with resultant lower midazolam concentrations. As
midazolam metabolites also contribute to the sedative effect
of midazolam, developmental changes in UGT-mediated
1-OH-midazolam and GFR-mediated 1-OH-midazolam-
glucuronide clearance may contribute to the observed
differences in sedative effect of midazolam across age groups.
A recent pilot study showed that critical illness and organ
failure are associated with reduced midazolam clearance in
pediatric intensive care patients
[102]. Also, when comparing
average midazolam PK data of children of similar ages,
relatively healthy children have higher median midazolam
clearances (10 -- 15 ml/kg/min) than critically ill children
(average 5 ml/kg/min)
[103] [104] [105] [100].
Similar to midazolam, tacrolimus clearance is increased
in young infants. In addition to age, tacrolimus oral
clearance is independently associated with CYP3A5 genotype
in pediatric kidney recipients. Children older than 5 years

3.2 Non-CYP oxidative enzymes
Although the majority of Phase I drug metabolism reactions
are mediated by the CYP superfamily of enz ymes, non-
CYP-mediated oxidative reactions also can play an important
role in the metabolism of drugs
[107].
3.2.1 Alcohol dehydrogenase
The alcohol dehydrogenases (ADHs) comprise a group of sev-
eral isozymes that facilitate the conversion of toxic alcohols to
aldehydes. There are five classes (I -- V) of ADH
[108].
3.2.1.1 In vitro
The ontogeny of individual ADH enzymes in vitro is differ-
ent. ADH1A (or ADH1) expression is high in the fetus, in
the first trimester, declining in the last trimester with low to
undetectable levels in neonates and adults. In contrast,
ADH1B (or ADH2) is absent in the first trimester, but mea-
surable by 16 weeks, with dominant expression at 36 weeks,
and measurable levels in adults. ADH1C (or ADH3) expres-
sion appears in the second trimester, with a surge in expres-
sion after birth
[109]. The mean ADH content of perinatal
infant liv er was ~ 10-fold lower than in adult liver
[110].
3.2.1.2 In vivo
ADH is the main metabolic route for ethanol disposition in
adults. Data on ethanol disposition are very limited in neo-
nates and small children. Neonatal ethanol clearance after
maternal administration was reportedly 30% lower than in
adults
[111]. A case report of accidental ethanol exposure in a
7-month-old showed first order ethanol clearance at a faster
rate than in adults
[112]. The alternative metabolic route
through caspase appears mature or even more active at birth
and may serve to compensate for reduced ADH-mediated
clearance in neonates and young infants
[110].
3.2.2 Flavin-containing monooxygenases
The flavin-containing monooxygenase (FMO) protein family
consists of a group of enzymes that catalyze chemical reactions
via the bound cofactor flavin
[113]. FMO1, 2 and 3 are the
enzymes active in xenobiotic metabolism. Numerous genetic
polymorphisms for FMO3 have been identified, as reviewed
previously, and their effects on clinical drug therapy are still
relatively unclear
[114].
3.2.2.1 In vitro
Hepatic FMO1 and FMO3 show opposite developmental
patterns. FMO1 protein is highly present throughout fetal
life with the highest levels before 15 weeks of gestation and
a subsequent decline during pregnancy. At 3 days postpartum,
no FMO1 protein was detected. In contrast, FMO3 levels
were low to undetectable in the fetus, with low levels in a
minority of neonatal samples. In the first year of life,
FMO3 becomes detectable in most samples, with an increase
to adult levels in post-pubertal samples
[115].Anin vitro study
in liver samples from children 2 -- 8 years showed higher
(almost two times) protein expression and activity of
FMO3 and CYP2C19, but not CY3A4, when compared to
adults
[116]. In these pediatric liver samples, voriconazole
metabolism by FMO3 and CYP2C19 was much higher
than by CYP3A4. In contrast, in adults, the main metabolic
pathway was CYP3A4 (with similar activity in childre n),
with minor roles for FMO3 and CYP2C19.
3.2.2.2 In vivo
In vitro-- in vivo scaling of the in vitro voriconazole data sug-
gested four times higher in vivo clearance in older children,
which is in line with existing voriconazole PK data that also
show much higher voriconazole clearance in children versus
adults.
[116]. Therefore, using voriconazole at recommended
doses for adults may lead to clinical failures in children.
3.3 Glucuronidation
The UGTs are responsible for the glucuronidation of hun-
dreds of hydrophobic endogenous and xenobiotic com-
pounds. The ontogeny and genetics of UGTs have been
extensively reviewed
[117,118].
3.3.1 In vitro overall UGT
In vitro ontogeny data are still very limited. In fetal livers,
mRNA transcription levels and activity towards UGT sub-
strates were low (1 -- 10% of adult levels) for UGT1A1,
UGT1A3, UGT2B6, UGT2B15 and UGT2B17
[117,119].
After birth, UGT1A9 and UGT2B4 transcription levels
were significantly lower in infants (6 to 18 -- 24 months)
than in older chil dren and adults,
[120], while UGT1A4 activ-
ity seems to reach maximum (adult) levels at 1.4 years of
age
[121]. The other UGTs studied showed no difference in
transcript levels between pediatric (7 -- 24 months of age)
and adult samples.
In 27 liver s spanning from 0 to 20 years of age, overall
UGT activity in vitro reached maximum levels by 20 months
of age using the pan-specific UGT substrate 4-methylumbel-
liferone, when applying a maturation model to the data
points. However, when looki ng at the original data, maxi-
mum activity is already observed at 8 months of age. An
important limitation of this study is the small number of
samples from children < 2 years of age (n = 8) and a lac k of
samples between 1 and 2 years of age
[121].
3.3.2 In vivo
3.3.2.1 UGT1A1
The polymorphically expressed UGT1A1 is involved in the
metabolism of bilirubin. Low UGT1A1 activity is associated
with unconjugated hype rbilirubinemia. As not all infants
develop this symptom after birth, additional factors to

thereby passing the threshold for pathological hyperbilirubi-

SN-38, the active metabol ite of irinotecan, is me tabolized

[122]. Genetic polymorphisms in

reduced enzyme and transporter activity were associated with
prolonged neutropenia after irinotecan-based chemotherapy
in a 10-year-old child
[123].
3.3.2.2 UGT2B7
An important substrate of UGT2B7 is morphine. In line with
low UGT2B7 activity after birth, morphine clearance is low
in children < 10 days of age, with a fast increase in the first
months of life
[119,124]. Pooling existing morphine clearance
data in a population PK simulation, it was simulated that
equivalent plasma concentrations can be reached using allo-
metric scaling of infusion rate (5 µg/kg
1.44
/h) in children up
to 1 year of age
[124]. For example, this amounts to 13 µg/
kg/h for a 10 kg infant and 9 µg/kg/h for a 4 kg infant. In
addition, neonates < 10 days of age needed a 50% dose reduc-
tion to reach equivalent morphine exposure, consequent to
lower morphine glucuronidation. In preterm infants, matura-
tion of morphine clearance is slower than in term infants
[125].
These findings suggest that current morphine infusion rates
used in neonates (10 -- 30 µg/kg/h) may be too high , possibly
leading to higher adverse events rates in this population.
Indeed, in a randomized controlled trial comparing two
morphine dosing regimens, neonates < 1 week of age needed
significantly less morphine than older children (7.5 vs
10 -- 20 µg/kg/h), although dosing requirements in this study
were not as low as expected based on the PK data
[126].
4. Extra hepatic drug metabolism
In addition to the liver, drug metabolizing enzymes are also
found in other organs, such as intestine, kidney, lung and
brain. The impact of development on the activity of these
enzymes is largely unknown. In intestinal biopsy specimens
from 104 children aged 2 weeks to 17 years, there was a statis-
tically significant increase in CYP3A4 expression and activity
with age. CYP3A4 was practically absent in the fetal duodenum
and expressed at relatively low levels in the neonate
[127].In
another study, CYP3A4/5 expression declined from infants
(1 month to 1 year) to older children
[128].Theauthorssuggest
post-transcriptional regulation of enzyme expression, but this
has not been studied further. In line with decreased intestinal
CYP3A4 activity in the neonate, an increased average oral bio-
availability of oral midazolam was observed in preterm infants
when compared to adults: mean 50 versus 30%
[129].
Koren and co-workers showed that pediatric oncology
patients younger than 3 years of age are more vulnerable to
ifosfamide-induced nephrotoxicity than older children and
adults
[130]. CYP2B6 and CYP3A4 are involved in the metab-
olism of ifosfamide into its nephrotoxic metabolite, chloroa-
cetaldehyde
[131]. In their search to elucidate the underlying
mechanism of their observation, the same researchers showed
that both CYP2B6 and CYP3A4 are present in the kidney of
young children. The exact developmental pattern of these
renal enzymes could not be determined due to the limited
human kidney samples, but in pig kidney tissue samples,
ifosfamide clearance was low in neonatal, but higher in pedi-
atric than in adult kidney samples. This finding supports
increased renal CYP3A4/CYP2B6 activity as the possible
mechanism for increased ifosfamide nephrotoxicity in young
children
[132,133].
5. Conclusion
Drug metabolism shows profound changes during fetal and
perinatal life. These changes can be attributed to develop-
mental changes but are confounded by other factors such as
genetics, co-morbidity, nutrition and co-medication. Despite
extensive research, information gaps continue to exist, more
specifically on the variation in the first 2 years of life, the
interplay of co-variants and the impact of non-hepatic metab-
olism. Moreover, how these changes impact actual drug dis-
position, but even more importantly effect and safety,
remains largely to be elucidated.
6. Expert opinion
Drug metabolizing enzymes are important determinants of
drug disposition. The fact that they are not stable throughout
prenatal and postnatal life often results in different pharmaco-
kinetics of drugs metabolized by these enzymes when com-
pared to adulthood. Much study has been done in recent
years to characterize the exact developmental pattern of
hepatic drug metabolizing enzymes. Also, the awareness of
researchers and industry of these developmental changes and
how they might impa ct drug disposition in childre n has
risen dramatically.
In general, a picture arises for many metabolized drugs in
practice that their metabolism is low in the neonatal perio d,
high in infancy and pre-puberty while reaching adult levels
in puberty. This picture is too simplistic, but to convey com-
plex information to physicians, this may be used as a
starting point.
Hines et al.
[7] suggested three developmental patterns for
drug metabolism enzymes: high in fetal life to low or absent
postnatally, stable throughout development or low in fetal
life to high postnatally. Although these developmental pat-
terns have emerged from recent studies, important informa-
tion gaps still exist on the exact developmental pattern in
the first 2 years of life. This is mainly due to limited liver

samples studied over the full age range, thereby obscuring
breakpoints in development. Also, PK data from neonates
and infants up to the first 2 years of life are limited. Most
data are available from the immediate postnatal period (up
to 2 -- 3 weeks postnatally) and from older children. Co nse-
quently, as most changes are expected in the first years of
life, estimations of drug doses for this age group are still
surrounded with uncertainty.
This lack of PK data is importantly due to the ethical
and practical difficulties encountered with PK studies in
young infants
[8]. PK s tudies are only relatively easy in h os-
pitalized critically ill children. These children often rece ive
drugs therapeutically that can serve as surrogate markers
for specific developmental pathways (e.g., midazolam, mor-
phine, c affeine). In addition, arterial or central venous lines
are often in place, significantly reducing the burden of
blood sampling. Most young stud y populations reflect the
age d istribution of intensive care popula tions (i.e., mai nly
neonates). In contrast, blood sampling in young children
(< 2 years of age) poses restrictions in children without lines
in place, as blood is difficult to sample from a peripheral
venous cannula, explaining the relative lack of studies in
the infant age group.
Extended in vitro studies covering these specific age ranges
to enable the exact determination of ontogeny are probably
not feasible due to scarcity of liver tissue from this population.
Alternatively, efforts could be made to pool, and if needed,
collect more PK data from children in the first 2 years of
life. If drugs are chosen that represent specific pathways,
such as midazolam (CYP3A4/5) and morphine (UGT2B7),
these PK data may obviate the need for extended in vitro stud-
ies. The design of these studies should preferably include
genotype-based patient selection (where applicable), limited
sampling strategies by using very sensitive analytical methods
and population PK analysis. Simulations will provide insight
in the developmental changes of specific drug metabolism
pathways, which can be applied to drugs metabolized by the
same enzyme (mechanistic modeling)
[134]. In addition, the
existing in vitro data can be incorporated in physiologically
based-PK (PB-PK) modeling approaches. Preferably, the esti-
mations from PB-PK modeling should be validated against
existing or newly collected PK data. As many drugs are only
given to small pediatric populations, prospective PK studies
may not be feasible for all drugs. An alternative approach
may be ‘opportunistic’ sampling, where leftover material
from samples from clinical care could be used for PK analyses.
For several drugs discussed earlier, the observation that
younger infants often need higher doses than adults may not
be fully explained by increased hepatic drug metabolism.
Agreement exists in the PK community that the relationship
between size (e.g., in kilogram) and metabolic activity is not
linear. Allometry is the term used to describe this nonlinear
relationship between size and function. This term is used
based on the observation that maturation of different
organisms is often not dire ct proportional. When using
allometry, using a function, the relative higher clearance of
metabolic clearance in young infants is largely accounted
for. In contrast, in neonates this function is ofte n not ade-
quate to predict drug clearance. This is probably a reflection
of the maturation of drug-metabolizing enzymes in addition
to an increase in size. Different methods to correct for this
maturation pattern have been used either by adding a matura-
tion factor to the clearance equation, based on metabolic
weight (using power), or by incorporating a maturation
factor in the metabolic weight factor
[135].
The impact of alternative excretion pathways in children
should be taken into account when focusing on specific
drug metabolism pathways. Several examples exist; first, caf-
feine which is mainly excreted as metabolite in adu lts. In neo-
nates, where CYP1A2 activity is low, caffeine is mainly
excreted as unchanged drug by the kidney
[136,137]. There is
also acetaminophen, which is a drug mainly glucuronidated
in older children and adults. In neonates, however, sulfation
activity is more mature, and provides the main metabolic
pathway for acetaminophen in this population
[138] [139].
Hence, caffeine and acetaminophen clearance in neonates do
not adequately reflect ontogeny of their main adult elimina-
tion pathways. Similar examples are sirolimus for which novel
metabolites were recently described in children that were not
found in adults
[140], as well as valproic acid and voriconazole
as discussed earlier. Hence, simply extrapolating drug metab-
olism pathways from adults and adjusting dosing based on
their developmental pattern to use in children may lead to
erroneous dosing.
From the data presented earlier, it may be clear that factors
other than age are important determinants of drug metabo-
lism in children. Genetic variation in drug metabolizing
enzymes may add to the age-related variation, such as in the
case of tacrolimus. Genetic variation may also be obscured,
such as in newborn infants, for example, for caffeine, when
all neonates show a poor-metabolizer phenotype. However,
as may be seen from the tramadol data, this is not the case
for all drugs in the neonatal period.
Also, critical illness and other co-morbidity may signifi-
cantly impact drug metabolism. A very interesting study
showed that critically ill children with multiple organ failure
had a fourfold lower aminopyrine clearance, a nonspecific
CYP450 probe, compared to controls (0.22 ± 0.15 vs
0.74 ± 0.31 ml/kg/min, p < 0.05)
[141]. Extrapolation of
data from pediatric PK studies to elucidate the effect of age
on drug metabolism could be confounded when data from
healthy and sick patient populations are mixed.
Although subject of extensive study in adults, variation in
of drug metabolism development due to ethnicity has not
been studied extensively. Limited in vitro data show that an
effect of ethnicity is already apparent early after birth for
some enzymes, but not for others. This may be due to a
lack of power due to small sample sizes and confounding
factors
[119]. These findings indicate, nevertheless, that
future studies should be more focuse d on reporting of

ethnicity and the impact on drug metabolism in the
pediatric population.
It is important to realize despite our increasing
knowledge of developm ental changes that most drugs are still
being dosed on a similar per kilogram dose throughout child-
hood. Even dedicated pediatric formularies most frequently
present uniform (per kilogram) doses across the pediatric
age range
[142]. Moreover, doses for children < 1 month of
age are often lacking. An important limitation of our current
knowledge of developmental aspects of drug metabolism is
the lack of translation of existing data to the ultimate reason
why children receive these drugs: that is, how will these data
translate to an effective and safe treatment of the disease the
drug is given for? Recently, it was even stated more strongly
that it is unethical to study pharmacokinetics in children
without taking into account the pharmacodynamics of the
drugs
[3].
In conclusion, information on in vitro and to a more lim-
ited extent in vivo ontogeny of specific iso-enzymes became
available in recent years. The translation of our knowledge
to drug dosing guidelines that can be prospectively validated
is highly needed to improve drug therapy in children.
